Hi Abby, How are you? Sorry to bombard you with a non-design and non-work related thread, but I do hope that you might find this subject on music composition somewhat of interest because it's been a pet peeve of mine for 5 years now and now with adoption of HTML5 canvas and audio - I wanted to get your thoughts on web-based music score editors. I recently came across noteflight.com after previously using TuxGuitar (an free clone of GuitarPro) and thought it was really cool; but I'm not happy that it's an commercial software and cursory search I haven't found any good open source derivative. Not sure how you feel about this and what you know but I wanted to seek your expertise on few burning questions that I have: 1) As an dilettante, I think it's pretty dandy and fancy; but as a professional designer of music scores, how do you think Noteflight et al. stack up to Finale or Sibelius?2) What is the current general copyright stance taken by record companies and score copyright holders on third party transcriptions and upload them on the Internet? So suppose the person transcribed the score note-by-note *almost perfectly*? And suppose the person transcribed a score "pretty good" and claims it as their "artistic interpretation" of the original score? 3) With synthesizers and good note transcription, I'm wondering why sometimes MIDI composition still sounds stilted. Is it because the dynamics varies and is open to the performer's interpretation (although there are ways to annotate legato, sttaco)? Or emphasis on notes (e.g., vibrato, bends on guitar)? Or the rhythm within the rhythm (e.g., play a triplet in a straight or "swing" groove)? These are not really business-related but more for my own personal edification. So please only respond to them when you feel like it and thanks in advance for sharing your knowledge to my curiosity after pondering on these questions for so long, Best Wishes,Paul Cao
